.TH "skcipher_alloc_instance_simple" 9 "skcipher_alloc_instance_simple" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
skcipher_alloc_instance_simple \- allocate instance of simple block cipher mode
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "struct skcipher_instance *" skcipher_alloc_instance_simple
.BI "(struct crypto_template *tmpl "  ","
.BI "struct rtattr **tb "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "tmpl" 12
the template being instantiated
.IP "tb" 12
the template parameters
.SH "DESCRIPTION"

Allocate an skcipher_instance for a simple block cipher mode of operation,
e.g. cbc or ecb.  The instance context will have just a single crypto_spawn,
that for the underlying cipher.  The {min,max}_keysize, ivsize, blocksize,
alignmask, and priority are set from the underlying cipher but can be
overridden if needed.  The tfm context defaults to skcipher_ctx_simple, and
default ->\fBsetkey\fP, ->\fBinit\fP, and ->\fBexit\fP methods are installed.
.SH "RETURN"
a pointer to the new instance, or an \fBERR_PTR\fP.  The caller still
needs to register the instance.
